Agreements  has  commenced.  The  only  other  work  completed  by  DDD  this  reporting 
 period  is  therefore  a  technical  review  that  documents  all  known  geological  and 
 exploration data and provides recommendations for future work.  
 Difficulties  by  previous  land  holders  to  secure  acceptable  access  agreements  have 
 resulted in only limited ground exploration within the project area. The only known gold 
 exploration is soil sampling, and possibly 11 short RAB holes, in the outcrop areas about 
 known  historical  gold  occurrences.  The  adjacent  areas,  and  north  and  south  strike 
 extensions of the mineralized structures and greenstone belt, are completely untested. 
 The Cosmo Newbery project occurs on the boundary between the GSWA East Yilgarn 
 Survey  (P  B  Groeneveld  and  A  Riganti,  2004)  and  Northeastern  Yilgarn  Geological 
 Exploration  package  (GSWA  Record  2006/4,  April  2006).  A  large  amount  of  digital 
 geological,  remote  sensing,  mineral  occurrence  and  geographic  data  is  available  for 
 display  and  interpretation.  Due  to  delays  in  securing  access  agreements  to  the  area 
 useful  write  ups  and  desk  top  studies  are  also  available  from  previous  landholders 
 (Asarco Exploration, Fargo Investments / Intercontinental Gold and Minerals - WAMEX 
 Item13260).  Unpublished  data  was  also  provided  by  Alan  Maynard  (Al  Maynard  and 
 The  potential  for  discovery  of  both  low  grade  and  small  high  grade  economic  gold 
 deposits within the project area is considered to be very high. The project area overlies 
 possibly  the  last  unexplored  greenstone  belt  in  the  Yilgarn  craton  and  provides 
 significant  opportunity  for  discovery  of  new  gold  deposits.  Negotiation  of  an  Access 
 Agreement to explore Cosmo Newbery will continue.   
 2.  Location and Access 
 The  Cosmo  Newbery  project  occurs  in  the  corner  of  the  Duketon  (SG5114),  Laverton 
 (SH5102)  and  Rason  (SH5103)  1:250,000  sheets.  The  project  is  centered  about  the 
 Cosmo  Newbery  aboriginal  mission  approximately  95km  NE  of  Laverton  along  the 
 Laverton  -  Warburton  road  (Figure  1).  An  airstrip  and  basic  guest  house  facilities  are 
 available at the mission. Reasonable tracks allow access to all tenements.

 4. Regional Geology 
 The approx. NNW – SSE trending Cosmo greenstone belt is one of the most easterly 
 Archaean age greenstone belts of the Yilgarn craton (Figure 3). Good bedrock exposure 
 occurs in the central area about known gold occurrences, but the majority of the belt is 
 masked by surficial cover. Depending on interpretation used the belt may be either 26km 
 L  x  9km  W    or  52km  L  x  9km  W.  The  belt  consists  predominantly  of  metabasalt  with 
 lesser metagabbro lenses or units. The belt appears to be in fault bounded contact with 
 adjacent granites. The GSWA has mapped a greater than 1.5km wide high magnesium

 The  GSWA  East  Yilgarn  Survey  (P  B  Groeneveld  and  A  Riganti,  2004)  geological 
 interpretation  suggests  that  the  regional  scale  Sefton  fault  has  transposed  the  Cosmo 
 greenstone belt into possibly two distinct repetitions. The Sefton fault occurs immediately 
 west of the known historical Au occurrences. Note that this interpretation is different to 
 that mapped on the Cosmo Newbery (3442) 1;100,000 sheet (Griffin TJ and Farrel TR, 
 1998). As this regional structure may have exerted some control over Au mineralization it 
 will be important to establish its likely position and influence.  
 Clemens (1998, item 13260) reports that regional metamorphism has virtually destroyed 
 all primary igneous textures and greenstones are altered to predominantly hornblende 
 rich amphibolites. A strong penetrative foliation orientated 85° / 350° with shallow 10° N 
 plunge occurs in the southern project area but 80° / 340° and shallow 15° – 20° S plunge 
 is evident in the northern project area. Clemens notes a concordance between shear / 
 fault and foliation orientation suggesting this as evidence the shear systems exert some 
 control  over  Au  mineralization.  The  reported  plunges  require  validation  as  this  would 
 have implications during drilling of mineralisation.  
 Well exposed greenstone lithologies occur about the known gold workings in the vicinity 
 of the Cosmo Newbery mission (Figure 5). Regional 1:500,000 regolith compilation by 
 Geoscience Australia / GSWA indicates that the majority of the remaining project area is 
 covered by sandplains (mainly aeolian and alluvial) and slope deposits (partly residual / 
 colluvium  and  sand  wash).  Topography  is  subdued.  This  area  of  covered  bedrock 
 remains untested and provides good opportunity to test for undiscovered gold deposits.
